Q. How are you doing?

1. Start With a Personal Connection
Proper research is essential. If you know something about the recruiter‚Äôs interests, you can personalize your response. For example, if you discover through LinkedIn or a Youtube or Instagram or a casual conversation that your interviewer is an avid runner, you can say something like:

‚ÄúI‚Äôm doing well, actually! I‚Äôve been training for a marathon, so it‚Äôs been a busy but exciting time.‚Äù

This approach not only answers the question but also builds an instant connection. The recruiter will remember you as the candidate who took the time to find a common ground.

2. Don‚Äôt go overboard: Don‚Äôt start talking them through your CV or skills that you‚Äôve been learning, that is a bit too extra, this is about giving them a taste of your personality while, softly selling you as a cultural fit.

3. Highlight softskills: Whilst this is not the place to talk about concrete technical skills, this is definitely a question where you can subtly sell your soft skills like resilience and adaptability

4. Always ask the question back! And don‚Äôt be like, I‚Äôm fine thanks. Big no!

Here‚Äôs a simple sample answer that does all that, using the example earlier ü§©‚¨áÔ∏è:

‚ÄúI‚Äôm doing great, thanks! I‚Äôve recently started running and have resolved to prepare for a marathon within the next 90 days, so that‚Äôs been keeping me on my toes ‚Äî both literally and figuratively! It‚Äôs been challenging since I haven‚Äôt run before but it definitely has made me much resilient and adaptable. How about you?, How‚Äôs your week been?‚Äù

